<br>
I find it harder and harder to sit down and complete a piece I like from start to finish, but then again, when I pay close attention to detail I am always happy with the end result.<br>
<br>
So the question is, would sketching more often help improve my skills more than just going a single project at a time? or would I probally gain more skill taking every drawing from start to finish? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=shinjad>Shinja D</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/18/02 4:30:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4550.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://membres.lycos.fr/sinemetu/nface.jpg width=50 height=85></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Which improves skill more?</span><hr size=1> Maybe you should wait for the opinion of more experienced artists, but for me it's clearly a lot of sketching. Finishing something once in a while is good, but for me it's frustrating as well, because some of the problems in a full project just aren't solveable from where I'm right now. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=superrats>Super Rats</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/18/02 6:56:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4550.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.happysoda.com/images/avatars/anime19.png height=100 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Which improves skill more?</span><hr size=1> Repetition and drawing different thing help you to improve.  Sounds contradictory, I know.  The more you draw, the better you get, but if you always draw the same thing you stagnate.  Sketching is a very good way to stretch yourself.  When you sketch, sketch objects you see around you and sketch funky poses from weird angles.  It's just a sketch, so who cares if it looks like crud.  Think about volume while you sketch and you'll really get a lot out of it.<br>
<br>
But, don't underestimate what finishing a drawing teaches you though.  It's important to do both.  You don't have to finish the majority of what you sketch.  That would be insane. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=<br>
