<a href="http://comicgeek.hyperboards.com/index.cgi"><b>ComicGeek BBS</b></a>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kennygeeze>Kenny Geeze</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/18/02 12:56:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4550.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.lespaul.com/menu1/deluxe.jpg width=080 height=110></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Which improves skill more?</span><hr size=1> Something you can try for an excersise.<br>
Draw a fully detailed finished piece with challenging subject matter. A person in a complicated pose, or foreshortening, or complicated perspective. Something like that.<br>
As you complete it, note what specific difficulties you had with it. Any particular area you had to erase and re-try more than one.<br>
Whatever it happens to be is what you'll want to spend some time doing some quick sketches of in the future.<br>
I also agree with the advice above. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=steppingwild>Steppingwild</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/18/02 3:41:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4550.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Which improves skill more?</span><hr size=1> Taking a life drawing class really helps improving your skills, also take a figure drawing class. <br>
Buying a few books on figure drawing also help but is not that effective unless you have taken a class. For example I used to get confused while reading  the tutorial section here, but now that I have a few classes on my belt they are really helpful in learning the manga illustration style.<br>
But by all means copy not trace, your favorite art, then compare it to the original and see what wrong then fix it in another drawing. But try to develop your own style.<br>
I'm just an art student in community college and not a pro or anything but I think this is most helpful.<br>
<br>
Oh yes and have a notebook and fill it with sketches and ideas then you can use them in plots for a story or something<br>
