</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mightyquest>MightyQUEST</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.pcshelp.com/quest/realm/triforce2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/20/02 12:50:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4550.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.pcshelp.com/quest/explosion2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Which improves skill more?</span><hr size=1> It depends what you're inmproving. For people, starting with sketches helps me the most. For effects -- shading, inking, perspective -- and details such as hair and eyes, I need to go from start to finish for it to help me much. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub92.ezboard.com/bherosreality"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.pcshelp.com/quest/realm/herosreality-minibanner.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tehbigd>Teh Big D</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/20/02 5:48:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4550.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://sg.geocities.com/teh_big_d/liljulie2.txt width=49 height=50></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Which improves skill more?</span><hr size=1> Here's a general way to approach drawing. Always sketch, keep a sketchbook with you 24/7, sleep with it under your pillow, and doodle when you zone.<br>
Once a week, put serious effort into drawing the most detailed, clean peice you can muster.<br>
<br>
Bada-boom, quick improvement.<br>
<br>
Most people I've met don't do nearly enough sketching, and only want to focus on the details, 98% of your drawings should be sketches. This is counting the loads and loads of crap that you'll very likely produce (hey, sketching can be erratic), scribbles, doodles, and funky-fresh-dairy-pimps. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bigtyme>BIGTYME</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator <img src=http://contest.polykarbon.com/badge1.gif></span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/20/02 7:27:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4550.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.users.qwest.net/~sbrooks4/bigworm.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Which improves skill more?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Most people I've met don't do nearly enough sketching, and only want to focus on the details, 98% of your drawings should be sketches. This is counting the loads and loads of crap that you'll very likely produce (hey, sketching can be erratic), scribbles, doodles, and funky-fresh-dairy-pimps.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
